textDelta: International trade will almost always benefit both countries, so why do countries try to protect their own firms from exposure to the world market? One answer lies in the fact that international trade is costly. Even a small tariff can have a large effect on trade flows. Firms are tempted to lobby for protection when foreign competition increases. Another answer is that governments often provide subsidies to firms. These subsidies lower the cost of production, making foreign competition less threatening. A third answer is that governments often impose regulations. These regulations may protect consumers, but they also raise costs. Foreign firms are less likely to enter markets where the cost of doing business is higher. Trade policy is always difficult.
